Esso, Lion Forest, MISC, Mycron Steel: Malaysia Equity Preview

-- B y   C h o n g   P o o i   K o o n   a n d   B a r r y   P o r t e r
-- 
2011-09-02T00:20:07Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-02/esso-lion-forest-misc-mycron-steel-malaysia-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
may have unusual moves in  Malaysia  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the previous close, unless
stated otherwise.  Malaysia’s  FTSE Bursa Malaysia KLCI (FBMKLCI)  Index rose 2.46 points,
or 0.2 percent, to 1,447.27 on Aug. 29. The stock market was
closed from Aug. 30 to Sept. 1 for public holidays.        Esso Malaysia Bhd. (ESSO)  : San Miguel Corp. will spend
$200 million to renovate Esso’s gasoline stations in Malaysia
once it completes a planned takeover, President Ramon Ang said
on Aug. 29. This is in addition to $1 billion to upgrade its
refinery, Ang told Bloomberg News. Esso was unchanged at 3.63
ringgit.        Lion Forest Industries Bhd. (POS)  : The timber and
building materials supplier will buy land in Cambodia for $26.1
million for palm oil and rubber concessions, according to an
exchange filing. The stock rose 1.4 percent to 1.44 ringgit.  MISC Bhd. (MISC)  : Standard & Poor’s downgraded its
credit rating for the world’s largest owner-operator of
liquefied natural gas tankers to BBB+ from A-. The Kuala Lumpur-
based group’s financial metrics have deteriorated due to its
debt-funded investments and exposure to “weak” market prices
in several shipping segments, S&P said in a report. The stock
rose 2.8 percent to 6.97 ringgit.  Mycron Steel Bhd. (MSB)  : The steelmaker reported fourth-
quarter net loss of 3.3 million ringgit compared with net income
of 3.3 million ringgit a year earlier, according to a stock
exchange statement. The stock slid 4.4 percent to 43 sen on Aug.
26.  Opcom Holdings Bhd. (OHB)  : The supplier of fiber optic
cables said its shares will trade ex-dividend on Sept. 14,
according to an exchange filing. It earlier declared a special
dividend of 22.5 sen per share. Opcon gained 1.9 percent to 81.5
sen.       Xidelang Holdings Bhd. (XIDE MK): The Chinese footwear
maker said second-quarter profit rose 8 percent to 20.8 million
ringgit as sales climbed, according to an exchange filing. Its
shares were unchanged at 30 sen.  To contact the reporters on this story:
